bmo: Short answer: add a tiny “progress” tool the agent can call immediately to print a status line before doing any heavy thinking/work. Then use it at the start of complex turns and before long operations.

What I changed (minimal, working now)
- Added a new tool: bmo://tools/progress.mjs
  - Purpose: emit a short status line via the core prelude logging (no-op otherwise).
  - Schema: name=progress, params: message (required), stage (optional), reason (optional).
- Hot-reloaded tools and verified with a test call.
- Documented the tool in bmo-tools/BMO_AGENTS.md Tool Registry.
- Committed these self-improvement changes to the bmo source (not your project).

Results of the change
- You’ll see immediate terminal feedback as soon as I start a complex task, e.g.:
  - progress msg=Planning…
  - progress msg=Reading files stage=1/3
  - progress msg=Running checks stage=2/3
  - progress msg=Summarizing results stage=3/3
- This avoids “silent minutes” while the LLM plans or before it runs expensive tools.

How I’ll use it going forward
- Emit progress at the start of complex turns (“Planning…”).
- Emit progress before expensive steps (large file scans, long commands, network calls).
- Optionally include a simple stage label like 1/3, 2/3, 3/3 so you see coarse progress.

Files changed
- Added: bmo://tools/progress.mjs
- Updated: bmo://bmo-tools/BMO_AGENTS.md (Tool Registry entry)
- Tools reloaded and verified.

If you want more later
- A periodic heartbeat/spinner from the runtime (would require touching index.mjs).
- A user preference to silence or throttle progress lines.
- Auto-emitting progress when a single tool runs longer than N seconds.

For now, this is the smallest viable change that produces immediate feedback without touching the core runtime.
